That is a very important insight. If you prefer the Business side of things (Strategy, Management, Consulting), moving these simulations to the Projects section is actually better for you.
Why? Because "Governance" and "Security Awareness" are business-facing functions. By framing them as specific projects, you show you understand how to execute a task, not just hold a job title.
Here is the exact content to copy and paste into your Projects section. I have rewritten them to highlight Business Impact, Risk Management, and Communication—skills that bridge the gap between Tech and Business.
1. Goldman Sachs Project Entry
Project Name: IT Security & Governance Strategy Simulation
Associated with: Goldman Sachs (Forage)
Skills: Governance Risk & Compliance (GRC), Strategic Communication, Password Security
Description:
> Acted as a Governance Analyst to evaluate the organization's security posture and bridge the gap between technical flaws and business leadership.
> • Vulnerability Assessment: Identified critical risks in the company’s password management system, specifically the use of outdated hashing algorithms.
> • Strategic Reporting: Authored a comprehensive executive memo for the Supervising Director, translating technical risks into business impacts.
> • Recommendation: Proposed an upgrade to industry-standard hashing protocols to ensure compliance and protect user data integrity.
> 
2. Mastercard Project Entry
Project Name: Security Awareness & Phishing Defense Initiative
Associated with: Mastercard (Forage)
